posts.name: A-Frame
posts.note: A-Frame is a creative Asian and international flavors mix at this hip eatery with communal tables and patio dining. You need to try the baby back ribs, and beer can chicken. If you're there on Sunday get the all-you-can-eat chicken which consists of three types of chicken, fries, corn, and Hawaiian buns.

posts.name: Azla Ethiopian Vegan
posts.note: Azla Ethiopian Vegan is a casual, cheery counter-serve with small tables specializing in vegan renditions of Ethiopian dishes.

posts.name: Bangkok West Thai
posts.note: Bangkok West Thai serves Thai standards (plus a few Chinese dishes) in a serene space with gold walls and white tablecloths.

posts.name: Batter Fish Food Truck
posts.note: Most locals agree that BatterFish food Truck serves the best fish and chips in LA. Even better, this bright yellow truck usually serves their famous seafood on the scenic streets of Santa Monica. Make sure to try the homemade tartar sauce on their fresh fish. For something different give the chili catfish a go.

posts.name: Beachwood Cafe
posts.note: Beachwood Cafe is a made-from-scratch American eatery with vegan and vegetarian options, plus wine and craft brews. They first opened its doors on March 1, 2012, serves modern American cuisine laced with Asian, Scandinavian, and Mediterranean influences, all made with the highest quality, in-season ingredients.

posts.name: Beer Belly
posts.note: Beer Belly is a casual spot for brews and gourmet comfort food such as duck-fat fries and grilled cheese with bacon or order the Duck French Dip sandwich or a few of their other duck dishes. NOTE: They have multiple locations.

posts.name: Belcampo
posts.note: Belcampo’s promise is to serve the highest quality meat anywhere —compassionately and sustainably raised on our farms, and of course, incomparably delicious. NOTE: They have multiple locations.

posts.name: Best Fish Taco In Ensenada
posts.note: Best Fish Taco In Ensenada serves Baja-style shrimp and fish tacos, plus housemade salsas, in a tiny, eclectic space with patio seating.

posts.name: BiergartenLA
posts.note: BiergartenLA is a contemporary beer hall with multiple TVs, offering craft brews, and an American-Korean fusion menu. Order the Koran burger with kimchi and Spam or the any of their sausages.

posts.name: Bludso's Bar & Que
posts.note: Bludso's Bar and Que is a sit-down outpost of a local Texas BBQ joint offering classic meats and sides, plus creative cocktails.

posts.name: Blue Star Donuts
posts.note: Blue Star Donuts is a minimalist cafe for grab-and-go brioche donuts in grown-up flavors such as blueberry-bourbon-basil and the best apple fritter I have ever had in my life and I'm in my mid 50's. Couldn't believe there is now a few Blue Star Donuts in the Los Angles area. You need to try one of their apple fritters, but any of their donuts will not steer you wrong. NOTE: They have multiple locations.

posts.name: Broken Spanish
posts.note: Broken Spanish serves sophisticated Mexican dishes and cocktails offered in a sleek, glass-lined space with rustic details.

posts.name: The Bun Shop
posts.note: The Bun Shop is a chic, brick-and-mortar outpost of a popular food truck, serving steamed bao buns and other bites. The Bun shop takes fluffy bao buns sourced from a Chinese baker, then stuff them with fillings inspired by classic Korean cuisine. Another standout is the Kalbi. A marinade that features sesame oil and soy sauce, as well as apple cider vinegar and cola, lends sweet and tangy notes to the beef, which comes piled on an aioli-slicked bun along with fresh greens and a tempura fried onion. You also need to order yourself an order of the Ba'Corn Cheese.

posts.name: Burritos La Palma
posts.note: Burritos La Palma serves what Jonathan Gold has called its birria de res one of his five favorite burritos. They also serve a goat version from what I read, but I could be wrong. NOTE: They have a second location.

posts.name: The Butcher's Daughter
posts.note: The Butcher's Daughter is a bright, bleached-wood outpost offering vegetarian (mostly vegan) fare, and juices in a relaxed space. I'm not a big eggs Benedict person but enjoyed their Avocado Eggs Benedict with hash browns and a side of Impossible Burger maple and sage pork sausage. Even saw film producer Brian Grazer and his wife here.

posts.name: Canter's Deli
posts.note: Canter's Deli is a landmark deli offering a huge variety of hearty sandwiches and baked goods around the clock.

posts.name: Carnitas el Momo
posts.note: Carnitas el Momo is in a tarp-covered courtyard near 61st and Avalon where Carnitas El Momo sets up on Saturday mornings is tough to spy from the street, but the thud of meat cleaver against wood acts as a homing beacon.

posts.name: Cassell's Hamburgers
posts.note: Cassell's Hamburgers is a burger joint in the Hotel Normandie offering breakfast and classic American fare in a diner setting. You need to order the patty melt or the breakfast sandwich which is between two hash brown patties with avocado.

posts.name: Cerveteca
posts.note: Cerveteca is a counter-service stand for traditional Mexico City-style eats plus a few stray tables and chairs.

posts.name: Chego West
posts.note: Chego West serves spicy rice bowls and other Korean-Mexican eats. The humble little LA-in-a-rice bowl restaurant full of win and the color orange set out to reinvigorate the rice bowl. Slow roasted prime rib with creamed horseradish, or sticky-sweet slabs of Berkshire pork belly over hot rice and fried egg.

posts.name: chi SPACCA
posts.note: chi SPACCA serves meaty, upscale Italian fare from a trio of star chefs in a Tuscan atmosphere with worn-wood tables.

posts.name: Church and State
posts.note: Church and State is a rustic-chic bistro serves house-made charcuterie and other French classics, plus creative cocktails. When you're there, you should order a charcuterie plate. The more people you have, the more variety or items you will get on the plate.

posts.name: Delancey Pizzeria and Bar
posts.note: Delancey Pizzeria and Bar is a vibrant late-night spot for thin-crust pies and craft beer which has an outdoor patio. The items to order are the wild boar gnocchi or the Guanciale pizza.

posts.name: Eggslut
posts.note: Eggslut is a casual, egg-centric food stand in the Grand Central Market offering omelets and other American grub. Get the eggslut which is a poached egg with mashed potatoes in a mason jar. Plus, the Fairfax egg sandwich and the sausage, egg, and cheese sandwich.

posts.name: Felix Trattoria
posts.note: Felix Trattoria is Evan Funke’s take on traditional Italian cuisine, with pasta made on sight, right before your eyes.

posts.name: Grand Central Market
posts.note: Grand Central Market is a grand emporium hosting food vendors and florists, plus game nights, movies and other events, since 1917.

posts.name: Guelaguetza
posts.note: Guelaguetza's mole sauce is the star at this kid-friendly Mexican spot featuring Oaxacan fare and colorful decor. You need to order one of the dark moles. You can even order a moles sampler or get the grasshoppers.

posts.name: Guerrilla Tacos
posts.note: Guerrilla Tacos is a contemporary restaurant originating from a food truck plating tacos with local ingredients and a bar.

posts.name: Homeboy Bakery Grill
posts.note: Homeboy Bakery Grill started as a training ground for aspiring bakers and now employs dozens of Homeboy Industry trainees in both the bakery itself as well as management of the expanding business. The bakery supplies products for Homeboy Farmers Markets, Homeboy Diner, and Homegirl Catering.

posts.name: Homegirl Cafe
posts.note: Homegirl Cafe is an offshoot of a civic-minded local organization serving baked goods, sandwiches, wraps, and salads. Homegirl Café is an experience unlike any other where you enjoy delicious food, connect with dynamic wait staff and leave feeling good that your purchase is impacting lives.

posts.name: Horse Thief BBQ
posts.note: Horse Thief BBQ is located in the Grand Central Market window is offering smoked meats and gourmet sides, plus outdoor seating. You need to order the smoked pork belly or the southern fried chicken sandwich.

posts.name: Huckleberry Cafe
posts.note: Huckleberry Cafe fans line up for the sweets and breakfast treats dished out by this shop's prominent pastry chef. Order the pancakes with the lightly folded in egg whites.

posts.name: ink.sack
posts.add2: Los Angeles International Airport (LAX) - Tom Bradley International Terminal
posts.note: Michael Voltaggio’s ink.sack is a sandwich place that is a go-to spot for people. ink.sack is in an airport-terminal outpost of a popular sandwich restaurant offers artisan versions to go. So grab a sack lunch from there and bringing it on board is now pretty much the best way to avoid airplane food on a long flight. The sandwiches aren’t huge, which means you can sample a few of them if you’re a big eater. I have read you should order the cold fried chicken and the spicy tuna, with a bag of their housemade crab chips.

posts.name: Intelligentsia Coffee
posts.note: Intelligentsia Coffee is a high-end coffee bar chain is serving daily roasted brews in an industrial-chic setting. They have a great dark chocolate hot chocolate and espresso (four shots). Great atmosphere to have a relaxing cup of coffee, tea, etc. while getting some work done or reading a book. NOTE: They have multiple locations.

posts.name: Jay Bee's Bar-B-Q
posts.note: Jay Bee's Bar-B-Q's owner Beverly Neely has barbecue in her blood, as both her brother and nephew (Food Network's own Pat Neely) have been doling out delicious barbecued pork, ribs and chicken. You should order the BBQ sandwiches, ribs, or the pulled pork.

posts.name: Jitlada Restaurant
posts.note: Jitlada Restaurant is a modest strip-mall location doesn't stop foodies who flock here for authentic, spicy Thai fare. Jonathan Gold recommends the southern Thia dishes. Try the Kua Kling (dry curry beef), Khao yam (Songkhia-style rice salad tossed with dried shrimp, toasted coconut, lemongrass, kaffir lime leaves, and a sweet sauce), or the green curry chicken and order a side of rice help cool down the heat or whatever else Jazz recommends.

posts.name: Killer Noodle
posts.note: The Tsujita ramen specialists open a spicy noodle shop called Killer Noodle. The restaurant’s aim is for painful, delicious, and spicy food. Jonathan Gold recommends starting at level three out of six.

posts.name: Kismet
posts.note: Kismet is a minimalist communal spot for all-day Mediterranean fare, from breakfast to family-style dinners.

posts.name: Kogi BBQ - Alibi Room
posts.note: Kogi BBQ food truck first rolled out as the little Korean-taco-truck-that-could, peddling $2.00 Korean barbecue tacos on the streets of L.A. Little did they know that within a few short months, they would become an icon of LA street food, a roving symbol of rebellion, independence and the belief that excellent food can be had on a dime budget. NOTE: They have multiple trucks that move around the city.

posts.name: La Brea Bakery Cafe
posts.note: La Brea Bakery Cafe is popular for its handmade bread, this casual cafe serves sandwiches, soup, and other light fare.

posts.name: LA Farmers' Market
posts.note: The Farmers Market is an area of food stalls, sit-down eateries, prepared food vendors, and produce markets in Los Angeles, California. First opened in July 1934, it is also a historic Los Angeles landmark and it is a very big tourist attraction.

posts.name: La Mirage Pastries and Chocolate
posts.note: La Mirage Pastries and Chocolate serves exceptional quality Middle Eastern desserts and French pastry, including baklava, Knafeh, and cake. You need to order the Bouza, which is an ice cream made with mastic, a tree resin that’s the essential component of chewing gum, and sahleb, a flour derived from orchid roots.

posts.name: Langer's Deli and Restaurant
posts.note: Langer's Deli and Restaurant is an old-fashioned deli serving up hot pastrami sandwiches, and other traditional comfort food since 1947. You need to order the #19.

posts.name: Leo's Tacos Truck
posts.note: Leo's Tacos Truck has delicious Al Pastor tacos are better than ever with a taste that will leave you wanting more. You can order them by the plate full which most people do. The beef head, tripe, Lengua (tongue), etc. are outstanding too. NOTE: They have multiple locations.

posts.name: The Little Jewel of New Orleans
posts.note: The Little Jewel of New Orleans is part grocery store, part deli, this laid back spot imports culinary treats from New Orleans located in Los Angles Chinatown. You need to order the pork Po' Boy sandwich or the crawfish mac and cheese.

posts.name: Locol
posts.note: Locol is a conscientious fast-food spot with a simple design for breakfast, burgers and health-oriented options. NOTE: They have multiple locations.

posts.name: Longo Seafood Restaurant
posts.note: At Longo Seafood Restaurant Jonathan Gold recommends for dinner the roast pork belly; baked oyster; soy sauce chicken; pork belly with preserved vegetables; ong choy with bean curd paste. For dim sum he recommends the BBQ supreme rice rolls; oatmeal snow cap bun; salt and pepper squid; preserved meat turnip cake.

posts.name: Los Originales Tacos Arabes de Puebla
posts.note: The specialty at Los Originales Tacos Arabes de Puebla is, well, the taco árabe: a large piece of pan árabe (or a handmade flour tortilla; the pan árabe is not always available). Which is like a thin pita bread, is smothered in a generous amount of pork de trompo, or from a rotating spit, like tacos al pastor. Unlike al pastor, however, where the flavors are chile and pineapple-based. Other items worth your while, are cemitas and tacos de cecina. The cemitas are essentially a sandwich version of the taco árabe — a pile of smoking, tender meat on a soft, slightly sweet sesame roll. The cecina, tender and thinly pounded beef, is given a perfect vehicle in two corn tortillas that are stuck together with melted cheese. Ask for some rajitas, tangy strips of pickled pepper, which make a perfect accessory to the tacos.

posts.name: Loteria Grill
posts.note: Loteria Grill serves creative takes on classic Mexican eats plus a full bar keep this bright, airy chain outpost hopping.

posts.name: LudoBird
posts.note: LudoBird is owned by celebrity Chef Ludo Lefebvre and has a CityWalk stand dishing out fried chicken and side dishes with a French twist. LudoBird is quickly becoming known as a master of an American favorite, fried chicken.

posts.name: Mario's Peruvian and Seafood
posts.note: Mario's Peruvian and Seafood is a no-frills strip-mall spot for Peruvian fare including saltado (Peruvian stir-fry), fish and more.

posts.name: Mariscos Jalisco
posts.note: Mariscos Jalisco is a no-frills Mexican food truck offering cold seafood dishes, shucked oysters, cocktails, and more. Make sure to order the Taco de Cameron which is a fish taco.

posts.name: Mitla Cafe
posts.note: Mitla Cafe is an iconic, family-owned fixture since 1937 presenting Mexican classics in an old-fashioned dining room.

posts.name: Monti Carlo
posts.note: Monti Carlo is a dive bar in Koreatown.

posts.name: Myung in Dumplings
posts.note: Myung in Dumplings makes traditional Korean buns and dumplings offered in a simple, subdued eatery with a pictorial menu. They make some of the best dumplings I have ever eaten. My favorites were the spicy steam roll dumpling with pork, the boiled dumpling with pork, and the fried dumpling with shrimp.

posts.name: Nickel Diner
posts.note: Nickel Diner is a cozy vintage-style diner serves updated versions of old-school comfort fare, plus creative desserts. While you are there, you should order the bacon donut.

posts.name: Night and Market
posts.note: Night and Market is a small, bustling stop for updates on traditional Thai street foods with beer and ice cream sandwiches. NOTE: They have multiple locations.

posts.name: Nighthawk: Breakfast Bar
posts.note: Nighthawk: Breakfast Bar is a dark and cozy nightspot for boozy French toast, spiked cereal milk, and other breakfast-for-dinner fares, along with the pork belly biscuit boa. NOTE: They open at 6:00 PM most weekday nights.

posts.name: Original Pantry Cafe
posts.note: Original Pantry Cafe is a casual cash-only diner, open since 1924, dishes up ample portions of American eats around the clock. You need to try the chicken fried steak or the pork chop breakfast specials if they have them.

posts.name: Osteria Mozza
posts.note: Osteria Mozza is the lauded upscale Italian cuisine from chefs Nancy Silverton and Mario Batali in a bustling atmosphere.

posts.name: Park's Barbeque
posts.note: Park's Barbeque is a lively, upscale Korean BBQ restaurant with grill-it-yourself Kobe-style beef and marinated short ribs. They have some great Banchan which are small shared dishes with their meals. You should order the spicy braised cod and radish.

posts.name: Petit Trois
posts.note: Petit Trois is a cozy spot with Parisian flare offers classic French fare and a full bar from the team behind Trois Mec.

posts.name: Pizzeria Mozza
posts.note: Pizzeria Mozza is the brainchild of Nancy Silverton and Mario Batali turn out acclaimed wood-burning-oven pizzas and antipasti in busy digs.

posts.name: Primo's Donuts
posts.note: Primo's Donuts is a longtime, family-run donut shop offering a variety of flavors, plus muffins, scones, and turnovers.

posts.name: Randy's Donuts
posts.note: Randy's Donuts is a landmark 24-hour donut shop that lures locals with its selection of homemade classic donuts, bagels, and muffins.

posts.name: Real Food Daily
posts.note: Real Food Daily serves meat-free meals with organic, hearty ingredients served in an airy, happening space. NOTE: They have multiple locations.

posts.name: Road to Seoul
posts.note: Road to Seoul's diners dig into all-you-can-eat Korean BBQ from sirloin to squid amid simple surroundings.

posts.name: Roscoe's House of Chicken and Waffles - Anaheim
posts.note: Roscoe's House of Chicken and Waffles is a local soul food chain serving signature chicken and waffles, Southern sides, and more in a casual space. Each time I went I order the dishes in the 20s from their list that had fried chicken with sides such as greens, mac and cheese, red beans and rice (fits on two-thirds of the plate), cornbread, etc. along with a waffle on the side. NOTE: They have multiple locations in the Los Angels area.

posts.name: The Rose Venice
posts.note: The Rose Venice is an iconic restaurant in the heart of Venice, serving locals and travelers alike since 1979. Chef Jason Neroni’s menu focuses on local Southern California cuisine with an international influence from his world travels. The bakery celebrates American classics, as well as some of the original Rose bakery classics re-conceptualized with their innovative techniques.

posts.name: Rutt's Hawaiian Cafe
posts.note: Rutt's Hawaiian Cafe is a restaurant with sidewalk seating serving traditional comfort eats plus Hawaiian menu options.

posts.name: Salt and Straw
posts.note: Salt and Straw is a the popular ice cream chain out of Oregon known for inventive flavors and farm-sourced ingredients. All their flavors are great it all depends on what you're in the mode to eat. My favorite is their Sea Salt with Caramel Ribbons in a cup. NOTE: They have multiple locations.

posts.name: Simmzy's
posts.note: Simmzy's is a bustling, open-air pub with a rotating selection of craft beers and American eats, including burgers. NOTE: They have multiple locations.

posts.name: The Slaw Dogs Cafe
posts.note: The Slaw Dogs Cafe is a casual spot with gourmet hot dogs, sausages, and burgers with toppings such as kimchee and truffle oil.

posts.name: Sqirl
posts.note: Sqirl is a hip cafe that features global-inspired breakfast and lunch fare with housemade jams in a minimalist space.

posts.name: Starling Diner
posts.note: Starling Diner is a casual and stylish, independent local cafe serving updated diner eats with coffee and wine. Order the pot roast wrap with potato and polenta covered in gravy.

posts.name: Sunny Spot
posts.note: Sunny Spot is a colorful, funky, modern Caribbean joint, crafting inventive cocktails and jerk wings. It's another Roy Cho place.

posts.name: Super Tortas D.F.
posts.note: Super Tortas D.F. is a no-frills mobile eatery is doling out Mexican tortas stuffed with layers of meats, cheese, and eggs. Found out about this place while standing line for spit roasted al pastor.

posts.name: SugarFish by Sushi Nozawa
posts.note: SugarFish by Sushi Nozawa celebrates local sushi chain serving traditional rolls and sake in a chic, intimate space. NOTE: They have multiple locations.

posts.name: Swadesh
posts.note: Swadesh is a bare-bones establishment is offering South Asian groceries and cafeteria-style Bangladeshi eats.

posts.name: Taste of Tehran
posts.note: Taste of Tehran is a Persian eatery with small and large plates which offers a few tables for dining in. Order the lamb shank with fragrant and a side of hummus.

posts.name: Tofu House (Beverly Soon Tofu)
posts.note: Tofu House (Beverly Soon Tofu) serves traditional Korean dishes including more than ten combinations of flavors of soon tofu, barbecued galbi, bulgogi, spicy chicken, spicy squid, tofu steak, and the stone plate bibimbap. You need to get the spicy tofu soup to put over rice.

posts.name: Trejo's Coffee and Donuts
posts.note: Trejo's Coffee and Donuts is a coffee and donut shop from Mexican-American actor Danny Trejo, with inventive fritter flavors.

posts.name: Trois Familia
posts.note: Trois Familia serves small daytime-only spot for chef-driven French-Mexican brunch fare and smoothies from celebrity chefs. Trois Familia is the third restaurant collaboration between chefs Ludo Lefebvre, Jon Shook, and Vinny Dotolo.

posts.name: Umami Burger - Anaheim
posts.note: Umami Burger is a lively chain outpost serving elevated burgers and sides plus creative cocktails in a sleek space. Make sure to order the Original Impossible Burger which contains two impossible patties, grilled onions, American cheese, miso mustard, house spread, dill pickles, lettuce, tomato. NOTE: They have multiple locations.

posts.name: Venice Ramen
posts.note: Venice Ramen is a compact, simple Japanese eatery for house-made noodles in a range of broths, plus other specialties. No need for extra noodles since they give you so many to start with I forced my way through them. The two types of dumplings they serve are great too.

posts.name: Villa Moreliana
posts.note: Villa Moreliana serves pork tacos. The pork is slow-cooked as it is prepared in Michoacán, México, the traditional birthplace of carnitas!

posts.name: Wexler's Deli
posts.note: Wexler's Deli is a compact old-school, new-wave deli offering bagels and sandwiches filled with house-cured meats and fish. NOTE: They have multiple locations.

posts.name: Yardbird Southern Table and Bar
posts.note: Yardbird Southern Table and Bar is a traditional Southern eatery with themed decor, chicken, and waffles, grits and more, plus craft cocktails. You need to order the deviled eggs and the shrimp and grits. NOTE: They have other locations around the United States.

posts.name: Yuca’s Hut
posts.note: Yuca’s Hut is a longtime taco shack lures foodies with Mexican fare, including cochinita pibil, and carnitas burritos. Yuca’s Hut is the only James Beard Award-winning taco stand. Order the tamales or the tacos.
